The Ichimoku Cloud is a collection of <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/technicalindicator.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">technical indicators </a>that show <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="2" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/trading/support-and-resistance-basics/" rel="noopener noreferrer">support and resistance</a> levels, as well as <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="3" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/momentum.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">momentum</a> and trend direction. It does this by taking multiple averages and plotting them on the chart. It also uses these figures to compute a "cloud" which attempts to forecast where the price may find support or resistance in the future.

The Ichimoku cloud was developed by Goichi Hosoda, a Japanese journalist, and published in the late 1960s.<span class="ql-inline-citation" data-cite="1">﻿</span>﻿ It provides more data points than the standard <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/candlestick.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">candlestick</a> chart. While it seems complicated at first glance, those familiar with how to read the charts often find it easy to understand with well-defined <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="2" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/trade-signal.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">trading signals</a>.

The following are the five formulas for the lines that compose the Ichimoku cloud indicator.

